# Version-history protocol

After every request that **modifies existing files**, record one snapshot per
modified file via `scripts/version_history.py`. Use the request's feature-log
id as `--request-id` so the changelog cross-references.

## When to snapshot

- **Existing files modified during this request**: snapshot at the END of the
  request, after all edits are settled (one snapshot per file per request,
  not one per individual `StrReplace`).
- **New files created during this request**: skip — there is no baseline yet,
  and the first edit to that file in a future request will create r001.
- **User requested a revert**: use `revert` instead of `snapshot`.

## CLI

```powershell
.\.venv\Scripts\python.exe scripts\version_history.py snapshot <path> --reason "<short summary>" --request-id <NNN>
.\.venv\Scripts\python.exe scripts\version_history.py list <path>
.\.venv\Scripts\python.exe scripts\version_history.py diff <path> --rev N
.\.venv\Scripts\python.exe scripts\version_history.py revert <path> --rev N --reason "<why>"
.\.venv\Scripts\python.exe scripts\version_history.py prune-local --keep 10
.\.venv\Scripts\python.exe scripts\version_history.py verify
```

Reason should fit in ~6 words; the slug is truncated to 40 chars anyway.

## Examples

```powershell
# Good: one snapshot per modified file, request id matches feature log
.\.venv\Scripts\python.exe scripts\version_history.py snapshot bot\discord_bot.py --reason "rename commands, add clearchat" --request-id 012
.\.venv\Scripts\python.exe scripts\version_history.py snapshot bot\engine.py --reason "route clearchat action token" --request-id 012

# Bad: snapshotting newly-created files (skip them - no baseline yet)
.\.venv\Scripts\python.exe scripts\version_history.py snapshot bot\brand_new_file.py --reason "new file" --request-id 013

# Revert
.\.venv\Scripts\python.exe scripts\version_history.py revert bot\engine.py --rev 3 --reason "regression in 014"
```

## Notes

- `VersionHistory/` is **tracked in git** so revisions are portable across
  machines; `prune-local` only deletes from your working tree (recoverable
  via `git show`).
- Never hand-edit files under `VersionHistory/` — use the CLI.
- Reverts are safe: the CLI snapshots the current state first as a
  `pre-revert backup` revision before overwriting.
